'''Nicholas Hugh Smith''' (born 1962) is an Australian philosopher and Professor of [[Philosophy]] at the [[Macquarie University]]. Smith is known for his research on [[hermeneutics]], [[political philosophy]] and [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Taylor]]'s thought.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Baker |first1=Deane-Peter |title='Condemned to Meaning': A Critical Review of Recent Work on Charles Taylor |journal=[[Theoria: A Journal of Social and Political Theory]] |date=2003 |issue=102 |pages=139–146 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/41791395 |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Levy |first1=N. |title=Strong Hermeneutics: Contingency and Moral Identity |journal=[[Australasian Journal of Philosophy]] |date=June 2001 |volume=79 |issue=2 |pages=296–297 |doi=10.1080/713659206 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/713659206 |accessdate=16 October 2018 |language=en |issn=0004-8402}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barwell |first1=Ismay |title=Charles Taylor: Meaning Morals and Modernity |journal=[[Australasian Journal of Philosophy]] |date=June 2004 |volume=82 |issue=2 |pages=364–365 |doi=10.1080/713659825 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/713659825 |accessdate=16 October 2018 |language=en |issn=0004-8402}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Anderson |first1=JH |title=Book Note on Nicholas Smith, Strong Hermeneutics: Contingency and Moral Identity |journal=Ethics |date=1999 |volume=109 |url=https://dspace.library.uu.nl/handle/1874/20322 |accessdate=16 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Redhead |first1=Mark |title=Review of Charles Taylor |journal=[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]] |date=2 August 2004 |url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/charles-taylor/ |accessdate=16 October 2018 |issn=1538-1617}}</ref>
